folder: Flushing Avenue & Woodward Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
1355 Flushing Ave., west side, between Woodward and Metropolitan Aves., showing the G. Thomas Smith farmhouse, later owned by his son. It is now owned by Andrew Bauer Jr. A new front has been put on this house.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Flushing Avenue & Woodward Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Flushing Ave., west side, between Woodward and Metropolitan Aves., showing the Cochrane house (No. 1359 Flushing Ave; tree in front of) in a set of four views. View No. 3 shows the Cochrane home alone, the house to the right of it having been demolished in the interim. The Jacob sash-factory (4-story), seen at the right, faces on Metropolitan Ave. In 1929 it was the Ideal Chair Company.
1922.
Views 1 & 2.
View 3: September 1928.
View 4: April 1929.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Flushing Avenue & Woodward Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Flushing Ave. (center of view), between Woodward Avenue (left) and Metropolitan Ave. (right). In the background is the 4-story structure of the Ideal Chair Company, which faces on Metropolitan Ave. To the right of it, on the north side of Metropolitan Ave., between 49th and 50th Streets, is an old house (cupola thereon). In front of the factory building is a peaked roof house, known as the Gabriel house which was erected by Todd the publisher. He sold to one McGovern, who sold it to H.C. Bohack Company; the latter demolishing same.
May 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Flushing Avenue & Woodward Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Flushing Ave., at the S.W. corner of Woodward Ave., showing in a set of four views the Woodward house. This house, supposedly erected by Joseph Woodward in 1750, stands 6O feet south of Woodward Ave. and in rear of 1471 Flushing Ave.,on land formerly owned by the Schenck family. In 1852 it belonged to the Schoomaker Estate; from 1869-1873 to N. Hausmann.
For more data see the N.Y. Sun, February 18, 1939

1922 1
Views 2 & 3: September 1928.
View 4: April 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Flushing Avenue & Woodward Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Flushing Ave., at the S. W. corner of Woodward Ave., showing four views of the Woodward house. It was occupied by W. Hausmann from 1809-1873. Prior to 1852 James Schoemaker was the owner. Views one and two show the front of the house; while views three and four show the rear of the house.
Views: 1&2 1920
Views: 3&4 1922
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Woodward Avenue & Flushing Avenue, Queens, NY
text:
Woodward Ave., east from Flushing Ave., showing at the N.W. corner (rear view 3 story frame) No. 1473 Flushing Ave. On the other corner is the Diehl house, operated as a saloon by one Schleider. The three story building was in a delapidated condition in 1934. This is a set of four
views.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
